Alright, so I'm not sure if it's weird to do a point-by-point response to a point-by-point critique, but

+block

–block


I agree about the 
Good call about this sentence. I've had some Discourse regarding the  clause (my argument is that for all we know, it is fully intending on moving the way it does), but I went ahead and trimmed the entire thing down.
Re: the scare quotes, I added them to acknowledge the possibility that the Stepdad was never  to begin with, it just appeared to be from our perspective. Perhaps there's a better way to convey this, however, or perhaps it would be redundant to convey it at all.
I removed the , but might only be approximating one. While it does respond to its surroundings, it doesn't do so in exactly the right way, so the question of whether it actually is sapient is still up for debate.
 is way better than what I had. Changed.
Good call on the weird sentence structure. Changed.
I don't think she'd immediately think her son was kidnapped upon merely hearing that he was talking about a stepdad he didn't have. Little kids say completely ridiculous things sometimes, and so I think she'd merely feel worried that something might happen to him until discovering that something DID happen to him.
The teacher didn't give details because the teacher didn't see the Stepdad either, she only heard Johnathan talking about him.
That obvious, huh? Rounded up to 150 kph.
Changed . Think I've maybe watched too many detective shows.
Changed . Sounds somewhat more clinical, and feels a bit creepier. I saw a let's play of a late 90s computer game involving extremely bad mocap recently which caused the heads of several characters to twitch and jitter, so that's what inspired me to have this skip do the same thing.
Moved the mention of being  to earlier in the transcript.
 is good.
Good call. Don't know what I was thinking with the pillow.
Tough but fair call on the  bit. It's a difficult line to tread, making an SCP that's amusing in a creepy/surreal way without going full lolfoundation. Removed it.
Regarding the redactions, I censored dates because I'd seen other skips with censored dates, but if you don't think it's necessary I'll uncensor them. I'll also try to think of a name for the hapless researcher in Incident 4092-1. I was thinking that Mrs. W and Officer J's names would be censored though, as they aren't Foundation.






